WEBVTT

00:01.752 --> 00:02.878
OLIVER PUTNAM:
My own son directing?

00:02.878 --> 00:03.921
- Dad, please.

00:03.921 --> 00:05.881
I-I need some help.
I'm drowning over here.

00:05.881 --> 00:09.259
- I understand. I'm just ridiculously
jammed with this case.

00:09.259 --> 00:11.261
- Hello, Mabel. This is Alice Banks
from Third Arm Gallery.

00:11.261 --> 00:13.096
We're a little artist collective downtown.

00:13.096 --> 00:15.807
There's just something
very compelling about you.

00:15.807 --> 00:17.851
I want to show you something.
- It's beautiful.

00:17.851 --> 00:20.103
- I'm glad you like it, because it's you.

00:20.103 --> 00:21.230
- Alright. What do we know?

00:21.230 --> 00:23.106
Bunny was killed with a knife.

00:23.106 --> 00:25.817
- Evidence keeps showing up
in our apartments,

00:25.817 --> 00:26.902
and we don't know how. I mean,

00:26.902 --> 00:29.655
first the painting over there,
now the murder weapon?

00:29.655 --> 00:31.865
LUCY: I think I know how people
are getting into your apartment.

00:32.448 --> 00:34.660
- In a shocking development,

00:34.660 --> 00:36.787
we've discovered
the killer's secret lair.

00:36.787 --> 00:38.830
- Is your friend from
yesterday joining you?

00:38.830 --> 00:42.668
Another waiter took my shift
and said you were with someone.

00:42.668 --> 00:44.586
- Not coming. And not my friend.

00:45.420 --> 00:47.005
I went over 20%.

00:47.005 --> 00:48.298
- That's too much this time.

00:49.091 --> 00:50.676
- No one else who needs it.

00:50.676 --> 00:52.010
CHARLES-HADEN SAVAGE:
Well, unknown caller,

00:52.010 --> 00:53.512
I need your help with something.

00:53.512 --> 00:56.723
- Hello, Charles. I've missed you.

00:58.267 --> 01:01.270
[ringtone, phone buzzing]

01:01.270 --> 01:04.606
[video game noises]
[ringing stops]

01:04.606 --> 01:07.609
- Yeah, baby. We're just doing this
family tree for a science fair project.

01:09.236 --> 01:11.238
Well, I took over.

01:11.238 --> 01:13.407
[game noises continue]

01:13.407 --> 01:15.409
Yeah. I'll make him do some of the gluing.

01:17.119 --> 01:19.496
Okay. Yeah. Love you, too. Bye.

01:22.457 --> 01:24.459
♪

01:24.459 --> 01:27.754
[laughs] My dad in the 1970s.

01:27.754 --> 01:29.923
There was no better time
to be in New York City.

01:29.923 --> 01:33.010
I know this only because
he says it constantly.

01:33.010 --> 01:34.928
Yeah, I guess if you miss
wall-to-wall porno theaters

01:34.928 --> 01:38.098
and trashcan fires,
the '70s were your decade.

01:38.098 --> 01:40.559
[club chatter]
But for my dad, they really were.

01:40.559 --> 01:44.313
- I've got an idea. Who wants to play...

01:44.813 --> 01:46.231
"Son of Sam"?

01:46.231 --> 01:47.733
♪ rock music ♪

01:47.733 --> 01:49.067
WILL PUTNAM:
See, he spent a lot of those days

01:49.067 --> 01:50.986
partying with friends and actors

01:50.986 --> 01:52.988
and artists, completely carefree,

01:52.988 --> 01:55.991
developing what he thinks
is his greatest skill--

01:55.991 --> 01:58.493
Knowing when someone
is hiding a secret from him.

01:58.493 --> 02:00.537
YOUNG OLIVER:
The object of the game is simple.

02:00.537 --> 02:02.789
If you're the killer, kill.

02:04.208 --> 02:05.209
[gasps]

02:05.209 --> 02:08.587
[impressed murmuring]
And if you're anyone else, survive.

02:08.587 --> 02:12.674
Most of you are innocent blondes,
but one of you

02:12.674 --> 02:16.512
is the Son of Sam killer...

02:16.512 --> 02:18.764
♪

02:18.764 --> 02:20.807
and I'm gonna find out who.

02:21.975 --> 02:24.061
Now, no cheating, Teddy.

02:24.061 --> 02:25.979
- Who, me?

02:25.979 --> 02:27.231
WILL:
You know, sometimes I wonder

02:27.231 --> 02:29.149
if he thought
the parties would never end.

02:29.149 --> 02:30.442
- Blackout!
[click]

02:30.943 --> 02:32.903
WILL:
Because for years, they didn't.

02:32.903 --> 02:36.365
- One of you... is the Son of Sam killer.

02:36.365 --> 02:38.283
[excited murmuring]

02:38.283 --> 02:40.285
And I'm gonna find out who.

02:40.285 --> 02:42.621
♪

02:42.621 --> 02:45.541
Is it you, my darling wife, Roberta?

02:45.541 --> 02:48.502
WILL: See, he's always been
an observant guy, my dad.

02:48.502 --> 02:50.879
It's basically impossible
to hide something from him.

02:50.879 --> 02:53.382
- Okay. Hold on.

03:00.764 --> 03:02.266
William...

03:03.725 --> 03:05.435
Did you just sneak out of bed?

03:05.435 --> 03:07.563
- Um... No.

03:07.563 --> 03:10.023
- Are you sure? You wouldn't fib
to your old father...

03:10.023 --> 03:11.650
would you?!
[playful growling]

03:11.650 --> 03:15.237
- [giggling] I admit it! I did!

03:15.237 --> 03:17.698
[laughs]
How come you always know?

03:18.156 --> 03:21.535
- Well, because everyone
who has a secret has a tell.

03:23.036 --> 03:25.914
Both your sockies--
Where's that sock? Ah, ha!

03:26.623 --> 03:28.250
Both your sockies are on,

03:28.250 --> 03:30.794
but it's well known that
you hate sleeping in your sockies.

03:30.794 --> 03:32.588
That's a tell.

03:32.588 --> 03:36.550
Your door was ajar, but you like it closed
to keep out the monsters.

03:36.550 --> 03:38.177
I just know you, Willie.

03:39.136 --> 03:41.972
Same way I know that Mom
isn't the Son of Sam tonight

03:41.972 --> 03:43.891
'cause she ate some cheese,

03:43.891 --> 03:46.852
and she only does that when she's relaxed.

03:46.852 --> 03:48.478
- You're amazing, Dad.

03:48.478 --> 03:50.898
- Well, you're even more amazing

03:50.898 --> 03:53.775
for realizing how amazing
I am so early in life.

03:53.775 --> 03:57.112
[baby talk]
Now, off to Dream Land, little boy.

03:57.112 --> 03:58.614
Shh...

03:59.448 --> 04:00.824
[whispers]
I love you.

04:00.824 --> 04:03.827
[door shuts]
[party chatter]

04:03.827 --> 04:06.830
♪

04:06.830 --> 04:08.332
[Oliver sighs]

04:13.295 --> 04:15.297
[indistinct whispering]

04:15.714 --> 04:16.757
[nervous laugh]

04:17.466 --> 04:18.467
[sighs]

04:23.931 --> 04:25.432
Teddy...

04:26.683 --> 04:28.060
You're the killer.

04:28.060 --> 04:29.311
[inhales]

04:30.270 --> 04:31.522
[sighs]

04:31.522 --> 04:34.525
[hushed murmuring]

04:37.194 --> 04:39.905
[laughter, applause]
WILL: But, it turns out,

04:39.905 --> 04:42.282
you can hide a secret from my dad.

04:44.868 --> 04:48.038
All you have to do
is not know what you're hiding.

04:52.501 --> 04:54.461
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

04:54.461 --> 04:57.256
♪ vocalizing ♪

05:40.507 --> 05:43.468
[metal doors opening, shutting]
[alarm buzzing]

05:43.468 --> 05:45.137
JAN:
It's good you're here.

05:45.137 --> 05:47.598
Being in a place like this gives
a gal a lot of time to think,

05:47.598 --> 05:49.850
and I tend to get a little neurotic.

05:50.767 --> 05:54.354
I'm worried about us, Charles.
Are we okay?

05:55.355 --> 05:57.232
- Are you insane?

05:57.232 --> 05:59.943
- You mean, like, legally? I wish.

06:02.029 --> 06:04.198
- I wanna know who killed Bunny.

06:04.198 --> 06:06.116
And I thought you,

06:06.116 --> 06:07.868
as a maniac,

06:07.868 --> 06:09.536
might have some insight.

06:09.536 --> 06:12.581
- Oh, you guys are really struggling
this season, aren't you?

06:13.207 --> 06:15.959
Mm, truthfully,
I'm behind on your podcast.

06:15.959 --> 06:18.504
I only get 10 minutes
of internet a day here,

06:18.504 --> 06:21.882
and mostly, I use it to watch
pornography and TikToks.

06:21.882 --> 06:23.383
Tell me about the case.

06:24.635 --> 06:27.429
- We know that Bunny was killed
with a knife in Mabel's apartment,

06:27.429 --> 06:30.390
and the killer composed the scene

06:30.390 --> 06:32.768
by placing a knitting needle in the wound

06:32.768 --> 06:36.063
to make the cops think we were involved.
- [shuddering] Ew...

06:36.063 --> 06:38.565
Yum. Any theories?

06:40.651 --> 06:42.778
- We were looking at Nina Lin,

06:42.778 --> 06:44.738
but we think that may be the wrong track.

06:44.738 --> 06:48.575
- Nina Lin? The Lululemon Gremlin?

06:48.575 --> 06:50.118
She's not the stabbing type.

06:50.118 --> 06:53.038
- Who is? A bloodthirsty bassoonist?

06:53.038 --> 06:54.289
- Not in this case.

06:54.289 --> 06:56.291
Though, I did stab my third one.

06:57.251 --> 06:59.127
You know, you really gotta know
what you're doing

06:59.127 --> 07:00.420
because, God forbid,

07:00.420 --> 07:02.673
you accidentally take out their appendix

07:02.673 --> 07:04.216
and save their life.

07:05.926 --> 07:08.011
- This was a mistake coming here.

07:08.011 --> 07:08.846
[bang]

07:08.846 --> 07:10.514
♪

07:10.514 --> 07:12.724
- How can you pretend you don't love this?

07:14.017 --> 07:16.979
The way we connect
when we theorize and speculate.

07:18.438 --> 07:20.524
It's just like how we used
to go back and forth

07:20.524 --> 07:22.734
about the last case.

07:23.485 --> 07:25.737
- You mean the murder you committed?

07:25.737 --> 07:28.866
- I don't get hung up on the details.
It's the feelings that matter.

07:30.617 --> 07:32.661
I know the real you, Charles.

07:34.204 --> 07:36.957
That last night we had together,

07:36.957 --> 07:39.501
we found our sweet spot.

07:42.296 --> 07:44.047
- You tried to kill me.

07:44.047 --> 07:45.549
- Details.

07:47.676 --> 07:50.470
Listen to what you said, Charles.

07:50.470 --> 07:53.265
The killer composed the murder scene.

07:54.308 --> 07:56.476
That's who you're looking for.

07:56.476 --> 07:58.812
A storyteller. An artist.

08:01.773 --> 08:03.192
- Go on.

08:03.192 --> 08:06.236
An artist never finishes
their piece in the middle.

08:06.236 --> 08:09.072
They stick with it till the end.

08:09.072 --> 08:11.533
Finding ways to stay close to their work.

08:12.159 --> 08:14.995
Is someone staying close to you?

08:14.995 --> 08:16.997
Does someone have a new friend?

08:18.540 --> 08:20.584
That's your killer.

08:20.584 --> 08:23.253
- So, you're saying it's not
raining inside where you are?

08:23.253 --> 08:25.130
- Skies are clear in this building.

08:25.130 --> 08:27.049
ALICE: Paint me a picture.
What are you wearing right now?

08:27.049 --> 08:30.219
Actually, let me guess.
Is it a, uh... [inhales]

08:30.219 --> 08:32.054
Is it a very, very sexy

08:32.054 --> 08:34.473
over-sized jumper circa 1993?

08:36.850 --> 08:39.895
Wait, am I right?
- That's cute.

08:39.895 --> 08:43.440
- I love that you have the same weekend
attire as Norm from Cheers.

08:43.440 --> 08:45.442
- How do you know what Cheers is?

08:45.442 --> 08:47.152
ALICE:
I'm from London, not the moon.

08:47.152 --> 08:49.154
It's funny, the turns life takes.

08:50.072 --> 08:52.616
There I was,
a posh girl being paid to party,

08:52.616 --> 08:54.576
working on the door of the rare club.

08:54.576 --> 08:57.538
But even then, I still had
this overwhelming feeling

08:57.538 --> 09:00.541
that I needed to check out the art scene
of jolly old Bushwick,

09:01.583 --> 09:02.668
where, now,

09:02.668 --> 09:04.795
my ceiling is weeping a brown liquid

09:04.795 --> 09:07.965
on the night I'm meant to be hosting
a full collective get-together,

09:07.965 --> 09:10.843
and I have no idea how I can get away
with calling this a water feature,

09:10.843 --> 09:14.137
but do you have any ideas?
- Jesus...

09:14.137 --> 09:15.639
ALICE: Jesus is right.
MABEL MORA: Um, hold on.

09:15.639 --> 09:17.307
I'm gonna put you on mute.

09:17.307 --> 09:19.560
ALICE: Yeah, I should go anyway.
I have to decide by 9:00

09:19.560 --> 09:22.521
whether I need to mop up this sewage water
or try and call it art,

09:22.521 --> 09:24.648
so... unless...

09:25.023 --> 09:28.402
you'd ever in a million years
host it at your palatial apartment?

09:28.402 --> 09:30.237
It's just a small drinks thing.

09:30.237 --> 09:31.697
[thud]
It's just passing the hat,

09:31.697 --> 09:33.657
a little get-together.

09:35.576 --> 09:37.369
No, Actually,
that's such an imposition.

09:37.369 --> 09:39.830
Please, just forget I said anything.
- You know what?

09:39.830 --> 09:42.249
I think having it here
would be a grand idea.

09:42.249 --> 09:44.126
- Really?
MABEL: Sure. I kinda hate

09:44.126 --> 09:47.713
the idea of being alone
in my place these days.

09:47.713 --> 09:50.549
I could use the company.
- Wow! Amazing! Okay, this will be so fun.

09:50.549 --> 09:52.050
I'll organize everything.
I'll get the wine,

09:52.050 --> 09:54.052
and you just don't worry about a thing.

09:54.052 --> 09:55.762
- I won't.
ALICE: Okay, see you later.

09:55.762 --> 09:58.765
♪

10:10.944 --> 10:12.446
[gasps]
WILL: Good, guys.

10:12.446 --> 10:15.365
Flap those wings. Scary, guys, scary.
[monkey-like chattering]

10:15.365 --> 10:17.326
[Oliver laughing]
I gotta say, Dad,

10:17.326 --> 10:19.286
what you've done
with the production value here...

10:19.286 --> 10:22.998
- Oh, it's just my old costume buddies.
You're the one who cast the perfect Toto.

10:22.998 --> 10:25.667
WILL: That's because I'm better at
directing the dog than the kids.

10:25.667 --> 10:28.212
- I just think it's so great
to have another Putnam in the theater.

10:28.212 --> 10:30.672
You know our family roots
in this business of show

10:30.672 --> 10:32.382
go back five generations.

10:32.382 --> 10:34.760
Showmanship and desperation must be

10:34.760 --> 10:36.929
the twin helixes of our family DNA.
[laughs]

10:36.929 --> 10:39.097
- You know, I wonder if that's gonna
show up in the ancestry test

10:39.097 --> 10:41.558
we had to take for
Henry's science fair project.

10:41.558 --> 10:43.810
Oh, by the way, we could use your help
with that, if you don't mind.

10:43.810 --> 10:45.854
- Sure. What do you need?

10:45.854 --> 10:49.107
Saliva I can give you right now.
Urine might take a minute.

10:49.107 --> 10:51.485
[laughs]

10:52.486 --> 10:54.404
- Eh, it's good to have you around, Dad.

10:54.404 --> 10:56.490
You know, any time you want to stop by,

10:56.490 --> 10:58.408
I know the kids will love it.

10:58.408 --> 11:01.745
- Well, let's... let's make it
a standing thing, okay?

11:01.745 --> 11:03.413
And I swear, I will never allow

11:03.413 --> 11:05.666
the commitment to my family
to take a backseat to--

11:05.666 --> 11:07.918
[text chimes]
Oh, hold on. I gotta get this.

11:07.918 --> 11:09.670
Oh! I gotta split. Okay.
- Yeah.

11:09.670 --> 11:11.421
- Alright. Henry! Where are you?

11:11.421 --> 11:14.007
[deep voice] There you are, baby.
Grandpa's gotta go.

11:14.007 --> 11:16.552
[normal voice]
Okay, kids! Rush hour is approaching,

11:16.552 --> 11:19.555
and the tunnel will be as packed
as Orson Welles' colon.

11:19.555 --> 11:22.474
[laughs]
- Kids, Dad, kids...

11:22.474 --> 11:24.476
- No, it's clever. It's clever.

11:24.476 --> 11:26.728
♪

11:26.728 --> 11:28.981
- Alright, let's go.
Let's take it from the top.

11:29.648 --> 11:32.526
- "...as Orson Welles' colon." [laughs]

11:32.526 --> 11:35.028
And everyone laughed, especially the kids.
[beep]

11:36.154 --> 11:39.032
Ooh. Is that the matchbook in question?

11:39.032 --> 11:40.868
MABEL: No!
CHARLES: Fingerprints!

11:40.868 --> 11:43.745
- Sorry. The Pickle Diner?
- Look. Is that blood?

11:43.745 --> 11:45.747
- Or is that a spot of ketchup?

11:45.747 --> 11:47.165
- Interesting.

11:47.165 --> 11:49.084
[beep]
Tell me, matchbook.

11:49.084 --> 11:52.004
Are you clue or condiment?

11:52.004 --> 11:54.882
[beep]
- So, the killer stabs Bunny here,

11:54.882 --> 11:57.801
and then leaves through the hole
in the bottom of my closet.

11:57.801 --> 11:59.970
- Hole in the closet?
This is new. I didn't hear that.

11:59.970 --> 12:03.056
- And during the escape,
drops the matchbook.

12:03.056 --> 12:06.643
- I must have come in right
after that. Bunny said "14" and...

12:08.937 --> 12:10.731
- Passage.

12:10.731 --> 12:13.192
- Maybe that's what Bunny said.
Not "savage."

12:13.984 --> 12:16.987
"Passage."
- Maybe, but it's all still a blur.

12:17.988 --> 12:19.907
- B-but if someone was running
through the walls,

12:19.907 --> 12:21.992
you would think you'd hear something.

12:21.992 --> 12:25.579
So, is it that you didn't hear anything
or you don't remember hearing anything?

12:25.579 --> 12:27.539
Where's the blur exactly?

12:27.539 --> 12:30.792
- I'm not... It was--
it was a hectic moment.

12:30.792 --> 12:32.544
- What's the difference
between hearing something

12:32.544 --> 12:35.172
and remembering hearing something?
OLIVER: Well, Charles,

12:35.172 --> 12:37.925
memory can contain both objective reality

12:37.925 --> 12:40.135
and subjective perception. For example,

12:40.677 --> 12:44.014
you remember being a huge television star,

12:44.014 --> 12:46.517
but I remember flipping past Brazzos

12:46.517 --> 12:49.019
to watch the Iran-Contra hearings.
So, Mabel,

12:49.019 --> 12:51.605
what do you remember?
- Not the Iran-Contra.

12:51.605 --> 12:53.106
- Oh, that one's easy.

12:53.106 --> 12:55.609
Ronald Reagan, who I didn't
always agree with politically,

12:55.609 --> 12:58.153
but whose acting chops
and hair color I respected,

12:58.153 --> 13:00.489
was opposed to something
called the Boland Amendment...

13:00.489 --> 13:02.658
CHARLES: Whoa, whoa, whoa!
He's skipping over

13:02.658 --> 13:05.160
the Carter-Iranian arms embargo!
- She doesn't need me to recap

13:05.160 --> 13:07.162
the whole embassy standoff.

13:07.162 --> 13:10.374
Couple of names to remember--
Robert McFarlane and John Poindexter.

13:10.374 --> 13:13.293
- And don't forget Weinberger and North.
- I wasn't going to.

13:13.293 --> 13:15.504
CHARLES: Or the Tower Commission.
OLIVER: I wasn't going to!

13:15.504 --> 13:17.172
I know all the players!

13:17.172 --> 13:19.716
Negroponte, Noriega, Hasenfus.

13:19.716 --> 13:22.135
- He forgot Ed Meese, everybody!

13:22.135 --> 13:25.556
- Yeah, I wasn't going to forget
Ed Meese, everybody!

13:25.556 --> 13:27.558
But, I'll tell you who we did forget...

13:28.851 --> 13:31.228
BOTH:
Fawn Hall! [laughing]

13:31.228 --> 13:34.022
- Oh, my god, shut up!
I don't care about any of this!

13:34.022 --> 13:35.524
- Well, you should.
It's worse than Watergate.

13:35.524 --> 13:37.860
Just not as interesting.
Okay, so...

13:37.860 --> 13:39.862
let's focus.
- Okay. [sniffs]

13:39.862 --> 13:42.865
- Does this matchbook
belong to the killer?

13:43.574 --> 13:47.119
- [sighs] Wouldn't it be nice
if it was just simple this time?

13:48.829 --> 13:51.665
If he was, like,
a lifelong matchbook collector

13:51.665 --> 13:53.667
or a regular at the Pickle Diner.

13:54.501 --> 13:56.753
- There's only one way to find out.

13:56.753 --> 13:58.088
♪

13:58.088 --> 14:01.550
- And here's my list of regulars.
OLIVER: Thank you, Ivan.

14:02.885 --> 14:05.095
- How can you still be hungry?

14:05.095 --> 14:08.265
- Charles, need I remind you
that there is a killer

14:08.265 --> 14:11.393
traveling through the walls of the Arconia
who can hear everything we're saying,

14:11.393 --> 14:14.396
and I can't think of a single,
safer location to work in

14:14.396 --> 14:15.647
that also has dips.

14:15.647 --> 14:17.858
Although these are pretty watery,
truth be told.

14:17.858 --> 14:20.319
- I agree. Not with
the whole dip obsession.

14:20.319 --> 14:23.197
Think it's a crime against nutrition.

14:23.197 --> 14:24.448
This is great.

14:24.448 --> 14:27.451
Half of Ivan's list is in Russian.

14:27.951 --> 14:30.579
- The person who did this
composed the scene

14:30.579 --> 14:32.289
to tell a story.

14:32.289 --> 14:33.999
So, who did Bunny know who was

14:33.999 --> 14:36.543
a-a storytelling artist-type

14:36.543 --> 14:38.670
or an artsy storyteller-type?

14:38.670 --> 14:41.715
- Okay, Carl Jung P.I.

14:41.715 --> 14:43.800
Maybe the killer is our shadow selves.

14:43.800 --> 14:45.344
Maybe it's my grandson.

14:45.344 --> 14:47.054
You know, he recently
got interested in the arts,

14:47.054 --> 14:49.556
although he's more of a...
mathlete at heart.

14:49.556 --> 14:51.308
It's hard to believe he's blood relative.

14:51.308 --> 14:54.228
- The only blood that we should
be thinking about right now

14:54.228 --> 14:55.437
is whose blood...

14:55.437 --> 14:57.064
- Uh, or ketchup.

14:57.064 --> 14:58.815
- ...is on the matchbook in the...

14:58.815 --> 15:00.984
[whispers]
secret passageways.

15:00.984 --> 15:02.069
- What?
- What?

15:02.069 --> 15:04.029
- [whispers]
Secret passageways.

15:04.029 --> 15:05.364
- [quietly]
Can't hear what you're saying.

15:05.364 --> 15:07.991
- The fucking secret passageways!

15:07.991 --> 15:10.494
SAM: Hey, sorry.
Did you just say that the killer

15:10.494 --> 15:13.247
is an artist crawling throughout
the Arconia's secret passageways?

15:13.247 --> 15:14.706
- I believe it.
- That's big!

15:14.706 --> 15:16.500
- Our fans! You rascals.

15:16.500 --> 15:18.168
Issue yourselves a spoiler alert.

15:18.168 --> 15:21.380
- You know, I think I know
about those passageways.

15:21.380 --> 15:24.800
I do mold removal in the building.
- But you think they're secret?

15:24.800 --> 15:28.053
- We are not prepared to confirm
any theory at this particular juncture.

15:28.053 --> 15:29.263
OLIVER:
Nice job alerting the world

15:29.263 --> 15:31.098
that we have no theories, Charles.

15:31.098 --> 15:33.100
But please, continue to wax poetic

15:33.100 --> 15:35.477
about our killer's inner child.
- Oh.

15:35.477 --> 15:38.105
So, their psychological
motivation is not important?

15:38.105 --> 15:40.065
They're toying with us.

15:40.065 --> 15:41.984
They have to get close to do that.

15:41.984 --> 15:44.528
So, is anyone new
trying to get close to us?

15:44.528 --> 15:45.779
[phone buzzes, text chimes]

15:49.324 --> 15:51.118
♪

15:53.453 --> 15:54.496
- What?

15:55.664 --> 15:56.832
This isn't that.

15:56.832 --> 15:59.751
This is just a friend who's an artist.

16:01.378 --> 16:04.089
Alice is not a killer. She's...

16:04.089 --> 16:07.009
an intimidatingly cool English girl

16:07.009 --> 16:08.677
I've been on a few dates with.

16:08.677 --> 16:10.095
- Dates? Like...

16:11.555 --> 16:13.223
Oh.

16:13.223 --> 16:16.894
- Oh. Look at the wheels turn slowly.

16:16.894 --> 16:18.270
So slowly.

16:18.270 --> 16:21.815
Don't you know it's very hip
to be bisexual these days, Charles?

16:21.815 --> 16:24.568
You're lucky. You know, back in the '70s,
I had to hide the fact

16:24.568 --> 16:26.236
that I had a lesbian lover.
MARV: You know,

16:26.236 --> 16:27.863
my daughter came out recently,

16:27.863 --> 16:29.573
and I was so proud.

16:29.573 --> 16:31.408
She says I'm dead to her,

16:31.408 --> 16:34.661
but could a dead man
"like" a Facebook post?

16:35.204 --> 16:37.372
- Anyway, Alice's gallery got flooded,

16:37.372 --> 16:39.416
so she's going to throw
a party at my place tonight.

16:39.416 --> 16:41.001
- And we weren't invited?

16:41.001 --> 16:42.961
- You're having a party
at the crime scene?

16:42.961 --> 16:46.381
- It's not really a party.
It's... very last minute.

16:46.381 --> 16:49.009
It's just a get-together.
You guys wouldn't wanna come.

16:49.009 --> 16:50.594
- Invitation accepted!

16:50.594 --> 16:52.930
I have the perfect waistcoat to wear.

16:52.930 --> 16:54.765
It's brand new.
- Can I go in this?

16:54.765 --> 16:55.974
OLIVER:
Is that a serious question,

16:55.974 --> 16:58.769
or do you think the theme of this party
is "open casket funeral"?

16:58.769 --> 17:00.395
[imitates punch]
Oh! [grunts]

17:00.395 --> 17:02.064
I'll get this.

17:02.064 --> 17:04.191
Oh, thank you.
MABEL: Guys,

17:04.191 --> 17:07.444
just please be normal. Please.

17:07.444 --> 17:08.445
OLIVER:
Okay.

17:08.445 --> 17:11.448
♪

17:11.448 --> 17:13.158
[door opens, bell rings]

17:14.660 --> 17:16.954
- Finally, some story progress.

17:16.954 --> 17:19.331
- After that episode about
the shit-talking bird...

17:19.331 --> 17:21.500
- And the baby-maker board president?

17:21.500 --> 17:24.962
- Oh, I'm just glad that they don't have
a theory pointing to themselves.

17:24.962 --> 17:28.257
- I like that Mabel's dating a woman.
Very progressive.

17:30.801 --> 17:33.804
[party chatter]

17:33.804 --> 17:36.807
♪ soft music ♪

17:37.975 --> 17:39.560
- Mm. Okay.

17:39.560 --> 17:42.437
The good news is you're not
the worst-dressed guest here.

17:42.437 --> 17:44.606
Pleasure to meet you, Professor.

17:44.606 --> 17:46.608
Did you ride here in a hot air balloon?

17:46.608 --> 17:47.860
- Mm-hmm.
- Ah.

17:48.527 --> 17:51.071
- There she is. The artist.

17:51.071 --> 17:52.447
I don't trust her.

17:52.447 --> 17:55.826
And when did they start dating again?
Right after Bunny's murder.

17:55.826 --> 17:58.996
- Okay, you're being paranoid.
Can our friend not have one nice thing?

17:58.996 --> 18:01.123
- Can I say I couldn't be more excited

18:01.123 --> 18:03.041
to meet the both of you?
- Oh!

18:03.041 --> 18:04.835
- And hold on. Charles,

18:04.835 --> 18:06.962
were you not in...
MABEL: Here we go.

18:06.962 --> 18:08.964
- ...that Swedish movie

18:08.964 --> 18:11.175
with that tempestuous throuple
that go camping

18:11.175 --> 18:13.552
and torture each other with orgasms?

18:13.552 --> 18:15.929
- You saw Encounter at Uppsala?

18:15.929 --> 18:17.681
I played the park ranger.
ALICE: Fabulously,

18:17.681 --> 18:20.142
by the way.
If it were in anyone else's hands,

18:20.142 --> 18:22.060
it would have just been
an average peeping tom.

18:22.060 --> 18:25.439
It's one of the most memorable
half-scenes of the entire film. Honestly.

18:26.231 --> 18:28.233
- And how did you see this movie?

18:28.233 --> 18:31.695
- I took a class on deviant sexuality
in Scandinavian cinema.

18:31.695 --> 18:33.697
By the way, I love your waistcoat.

18:33.697 --> 18:35.115
I used to have one just like it.

18:35.115 --> 18:37.075
- Oh, I-I doubt that.

18:37.075 --> 18:40.162
So tell me, how did you and Mabel meet?

18:40.162 --> 18:43.123
Because it's so impossible
to pry any information

18:43.123 --> 18:44.750
out of this adorable little vault.

18:44.750 --> 18:46.919
- Well, okay, why don't
you guys go to the bar?

18:46.919 --> 18:49.421
It's the door being used as a table.

18:49.421 --> 18:51.340
[party chatter continues]

18:53.175 --> 18:56.887
- I hate to say it, but I think
you may be right about our Alice.

18:56.887 --> 18:58.639
There's something about that story.

18:58.639 --> 19:01.892
- She's fantastic! She didn't do it.

19:01.892 --> 19:06.063
- So, some strange woman
praises your one foreign film foray

19:06.063 --> 19:07.523
and, all of a sudden, you trust her.

19:07.523 --> 19:09.274
It's the Jan thing all over again.

19:09.274 --> 19:10.859
- Okay. Uh, fair enough,

19:10.859 --> 19:12.486
but what are the odds
of that happening again?

19:12.486 --> 19:14.988
And you can't go around
thinking everybody's lying.

19:14.988 --> 19:16.865
- Yeah, I only think it if they're lying,

19:16.865 --> 19:18.617
and everyone has a tell.

19:18.617 --> 19:21.161
- Oh? Really? What's my tell?

19:21.161 --> 19:23.580
- Your tell is that you don't have a tell.

19:23.580 --> 19:25.707
You're just as uncomfortable as you look.

19:27.709 --> 19:29.503
I'll be right back.
- You can't leave me here.

19:29.503 --> 19:30.879
I'm not good at parties!

19:32.422 --> 19:33.799
Oh, hi.
- Hi!

19:33.799 --> 19:37.177
I-I'm nervous to talk to people
because I can come off creepy. [laughs]

19:39.638 --> 19:41.265
[party chatter continues]

19:41.265 --> 19:43.267
- Okay, zoomers!

19:43.267 --> 19:45.269
This shindig is flat-lining...
[speaker feedback, music stops]

19:45.269 --> 19:47.729
but thankfully, Dr. Oliver Feelgood's

19:47.729 --> 19:50.399
got something to jump-start its heart.

19:50.399 --> 19:53.026
A party game.
- Oliver, what are you doing?

19:53.026 --> 19:55.529
- Oh, I know we're all
too cool for this, Mabel.

19:55.529 --> 19:57.698
But you know who else
thought he was too cool?

19:57.698 --> 20:00.158
Andy Warhol. I knew him.
[murmuring]

20:00.158 --> 20:02.578
Taught him how to play
at the Factory in '79.

20:02.578 --> 20:07.040
- This is demented. I'm in.
- Wonderful. Step one, drugs!

20:07.040 --> 20:09.501
But, fair warning,
they may be a few decades old.

20:09.501 --> 20:11.670
Red before green, you're peeing clean.

20:11.670 --> 20:14.006
Green before red, your liver's dead.

20:14.006 --> 20:15.632
- What is he doing?
- He's either pushing

20:15.632 --> 20:17.384
Benzedrine or penicillin.

20:17.384 --> 20:20.679
- It's an innocent game.
Now, everyone get pilled out

20:20.679 --> 20:23.932
and prepare to travel back
to gritty-go-go-in-your-face,

20:23.932 --> 20:27.144
Dancin', Bronx on fire, let's go Knicks!

20:27.144 --> 20:30.522
Mean Streets. Taxi Driver.
Muppets Take Manhattan.

20:30.522 --> 20:33.817
New York City of 1977!

20:33.817 --> 20:36.236
And... blackout!

20:36.236 --> 20:38.780
[click]
It's a hot, sweaty summer night,

20:38.780 --> 20:41.158
and there's a madman on the loose.

20:41.158 --> 20:42.451
♪ funky jazz ♪

20:42.451 --> 20:45.245
The game is Son of Sam.

20:45.245 --> 20:48.749
Now, no one show each other your cards.

20:48.749 --> 20:52.294
Most of you are innocent blondes,
but one of you

20:53.086 --> 20:55.797
is the Son of Sam Killer.

20:55.797 --> 20:58.133
[slicing, stabbing]
[woman screaming]

20:58.133 --> 21:01.094
Each round, after I quietly whisper,

21:01.094 --> 21:03.388
"Blackout!"
[soft laughter]

21:03.388 --> 21:06.391
We all put our hands into the center,

21:06.391 --> 21:09.019
close our eyes,

21:09.019 --> 21:11.730
and the Son of Sam will secretly...

21:11.730 --> 21:13.315
pinch a victim like so.

21:13.315 --> 21:15.651
[gasps]
Ah! And that pinch means

21:15.651 --> 21:17.861
that you've just had
your head blown off in a parked car.

21:17.861 --> 21:19.363
Blammo.
[gun cocks, gunshot]

21:22.115 --> 21:24.743
Blackout ends. We discuss, we debate.

21:24.743 --> 21:27.079
If we vote for the wrong person,

21:27.079 --> 21:29.206
blackout, and so on,

21:29.206 --> 21:32.751
until we have correctly
identified the killer

21:32.751 --> 21:35.879
or every innocent blonde in Bay Ridge

21:35.879 --> 21:38.674
has been slaughtered by the Son of Sam.

21:39.174 --> 21:41.009
- Oh, I used to play this game in Oxford,

21:41.009 --> 21:43.303
although we called it Jack the Ripper.

21:43.303 --> 21:44.429
- No.
[music stops]

21:44.429 --> 21:47.182
We're in New York in the '70s, Alice.
Pay attention.

21:47.182 --> 21:49.726
You haven't even been born yet.
[music restarts]

21:49.726 --> 21:52.938
Now, everyone ready?
Get into the center.

21:52.938 --> 21:55.816
[excited chatter]

21:55.816 --> 21:56.942
Blackout.
[click]

21:56.942 --> 21:59.361
[giggling, murmuring]
Eyes closed.

21:59.361 --> 22:01.446
Wait for the killer's pinch.

22:01.446 --> 22:04.157
Three, two, one!

22:06.952 --> 22:09.162
[crowd gasping]

22:09.162 --> 22:10.539
- I'm so dead.

22:10.539 --> 22:13.709
OLIVER:
Ah. Now, would anyone like to begin

22:13.709 --> 22:16.420
the investigation with a few questions?

22:16.420 --> 22:18.964
- Charles is totally the killer.

22:18.964 --> 22:20.841
- Wait, that's not even a question.

22:20.841 --> 22:23.260
- Who else agrees? There's a question.

22:23.260 --> 22:25.012
♪

22:25.012 --> 22:28.015
- I'm no killer, Mabel.
I'm just a curious coed from the Midwest,

22:28.015 --> 22:30.142
hoping to kiss my first Italian.

22:30.142 --> 22:33.604
- Well, as usual, I find
your acting unconvincing. Let's vote.

22:33.604 --> 22:35.647
Who thinks it's Charles?
GUEST: Yep.

22:35.647 --> 22:37.983
- Sorry, but you've been found guilty

22:37.983 --> 22:41.445
by a vigilante mob of
bridge-and-tunnel lunatics.

22:41.445 --> 22:45.240
- You all have blood on your hands.
[gasping, murmuring]

22:45.240 --> 22:47.242
- You must now spend the rest of the game
over by that couch,

22:47.242 --> 22:49.244
eating pretzels in purgatory.

22:49.244 --> 22:51.788
MABEL: Mm, sorry, Charles.
- Yeah, me, too.

22:51.788 --> 22:53.874
OLIVER:
Alright! Everyone, back in the center.

22:53.874 --> 22:56.585
And... blackout!
[excited chatter]

22:56.585 --> 22:57.419
[shushing]

22:57.419 --> 22:59.630
Eyes closed. Wait for the killer's pinch.

22:59.630 --> 23:02.508
♪ Psycho Killer by Talking Heads ♪

23:03.008 --> 23:03.842
[giggling]

23:03.842 --> 23:06.386
♪ I'm tense and nervous
and I can't relax ♪

23:07.721 --> 23:09.348
[crowd gasping]

23:09.890 --> 23:11.391
[screams]

23:11.391 --> 23:12.893
[gasping]

23:12.893 --> 23:14.895
♪ I'm a real live wire ♪

23:14.895 --> 23:16.063
[guests gasping]

23:16.063 --> 23:19.816
OLIVER: Blackout after blackout,
the Son of Sam struck,

23:19.816 --> 23:23.362
and all efforts to catch
the killer came to naught.

23:23.362 --> 23:24.738
♪ Run, run, run ♪

23:24.738 --> 23:26.448
And then there were three.

23:26.448 --> 23:29.409
Only is it three? Or is it two

23:29.409 --> 23:31.328
and a psycho killer?
[song ends]

23:31.328 --> 23:32.704
- You play many roles, Oliver.

23:32.704 --> 23:34.915
What's stopping you
from being the murderer?

23:34.915 --> 23:36.750
- I know for a fact

23:36.750 --> 23:38.794
that you're the Son of Sam, Alice.

23:38.794 --> 23:41.213
- Moi? What's got you pointing
the finger at me then?

23:41.213 --> 23:43.715
- Simple. You have a tell.

23:44.424 --> 23:47.553
You play with your hair when you're lying,
like you're doing right now.

23:47.553 --> 23:49.179
- That is something that you do.

23:49.179 --> 23:51.181
- I like playing with my hair.
It's not a tell.

23:51.181 --> 23:53.559
- You did the exact same thing

23:53.559 --> 23:55.435
when you were talking about your life

23:55.435 --> 23:56.812
as a posh little art legacy.

23:56.812 --> 23:58.772
- Well, that wasn't a lie.
OLIVER: Wasn't it?

23:58.772 --> 24:01.066
You did the same thing when
you mentioned going to Oxford.

24:01.066 --> 24:03.151
- I didn't.
- Is this still a game?

24:03.151 --> 24:06.029
- You're not who you say you are.
Why did you really befriend Mabel?

24:06.029 --> 24:07.030
- Okay, this has to stop.

24:07.030 --> 24:08.574
- I know you're the Son of Sam

24:08.574 --> 24:10.325
and potentially worse.
[crunch]

24:10.325 --> 24:12.536
- Hey, pretzel boy,
you wanna help me out here?

24:13.745 --> 24:15.247
[crunch]

24:16.164 --> 24:17.374
- I know it seems crazy,

24:17.374 --> 24:21.295
but Alice came into your life
so soon after Bunny died.

24:21.295 --> 24:23.672
We thought she might be up to something.

24:23.672 --> 24:25.507
- And she is. She's lying to you,

24:25.507 --> 24:27.259
and everyone else here tonight,
aren't you?

24:27.259 --> 24:29.303
- No... Stop!
- Admit it.

24:29.303 --> 24:31.847
- You never saw his weird
Swedish porno film,

24:31.847 --> 24:34.099
and you are not who you say you are.
- Okay!

24:34.099 --> 24:35.851
♪

24:35.851 --> 24:37.227
Fine.

24:37.227 --> 24:39.521
I didn't go to Oxford.

24:39.521 --> 24:43.108
And no one in my family is rich
or is in the arts.

24:43.108 --> 24:45.569
But who wants to buy a $50,000 painting

24:45.569 --> 24:47.613
from the daughter of a plumber from Essex?

24:50.157 --> 24:53.118
I didn't think so. I've had to lie

24:53.118 --> 24:56.788
to create some legitimacy
for myself in this world.

24:56.788 --> 24:59.958
And, yes, I get the irony
in what I just said.

25:01.627 --> 25:04.421
And now, if you are done humiliating me...

25:05.506 --> 25:08.091
Game over, please. Thank you.

25:13.847 --> 25:16.350
[door opens, shuts]

25:18.560 --> 25:20.562
- Innocent blonde.

25:21.188 --> 25:23.190
I thought for sure she did it.

25:24.650 --> 25:27.653
- If this is what people
do at parties, I'm out.

25:29.780 --> 25:30.781
[Oliver sighs]

25:31.740 --> 25:34.743
[quiet chatter]

25:34.743 --> 25:36.495
♪

25:38.539 --> 25:40.457
♪

25:42.501 --> 25:43.502
[door creaks]

25:43.502 --> 25:45.212
[paper sliding]

26:01.979 --> 26:03.814
[elevator dings]

26:03.814 --> 26:06.692
[elevator doors rattle, shut]

26:12.406 --> 26:14.408
[knocking]
MABEL: Everybody's gone.

26:14.408 --> 26:16.410
[heavy breathing]

26:16.869 --> 26:17.870
[sighs]

26:19.329 --> 26:20.330
[sniffs]

26:23.542 --> 26:25.043
[sighs]
Brave.

26:25.836 --> 26:28.130
- I know. I'm a coward.

26:28.130 --> 26:30.048
I can't stand it when people
are mad at me.

26:30.048 --> 26:31.550
- Well, I am mad.

26:32.426 --> 26:35.220
At Charles and Oliver, too,
but especially you.

26:36.305 --> 26:37.639
You lied to me,

26:37.639 --> 26:40.184
and I'm not leaving here
until you tell me why.

26:40.184 --> 26:42.603
- It's hard to explain.

26:42.603 --> 26:44.688
I always knew I wanted to be an artist.

26:44.688 --> 26:48.150
Oh god, it sounds so trite
when you say it out loud, but...

26:49.568 --> 26:51.737
for me, it's true. [sighs]

26:51.737 --> 26:53.739
And all the things that got in the way...

26:54.948 --> 26:57.409
going to the wrong schools,

26:57.409 --> 26:59.411
not knowing anyone important or famous

26:59.411 --> 27:01.246
or even vaguely interesting,

27:01.246 --> 27:04.541
it felt like something
I could never overcome, so I lied.

27:06.043 --> 27:08.462
But I should've been honest with you.

27:10.380 --> 27:12.466
I owed you that.

27:12.466 --> 27:14.593
I didn't know how to tell you,
and I'm sorry.

27:14.593 --> 27:15.594
[inhales]

27:19.681 --> 27:21.683
- Everyone lies a little.

27:22.601 --> 27:23.602
I lie.

27:23.602 --> 27:25.771
- [scoffs] About what?

27:27.564 --> 27:29.900
- Remember when we went
to that Thai restaurant,

27:29.900 --> 27:32.694
and you asked me if I thought
the larb was too spicy?

27:32.694 --> 27:34.821
And I was like, "No."

27:34.821 --> 27:37.282
I was fucking lying.
[laughs]

27:37.282 --> 27:40.285
Also, whenever anyone asks me

27:40.285 --> 27:42.788
if I've heard of a band or a movie,

27:42.788 --> 27:44.414
I'm like, "Yeah!"

27:45.415 --> 27:47.000
I'm fucking lying.

27:48.168 --> 27:50.212
- [inhales] Are we okay?

27:50.838 --> 27:53.215
- I'm glad that you told me the truth.

27:54.716 --> 27:56.552
I have trust issues.

27:56.552 --> 27:59.137
♪

27:59.137 --> 28:01.306
- There's a band called Trust Issues.
Have you heard of them?

28:01.306 --> 28:03.308
They're really good.
[soft laugh]

28:04.476 --> 28:05.477
- Hey.

28:07.855 --> 28:09.898
No more half-truths, okay?

28:18.866 --> 28:22.327
JAN: [on phone] Wait, she's dating
an actual artist? [laughs] No kidding.

28:22.327 --> 28:25.289
That's like a criminal profiling
hole-in-one.

28:25.289 --> 28:27.332
CHARLES:
Yeah, but, uh, now I'm not so sure.

28:27.332 --> 28:31.086
JAN: Why? Is she flirting with you?
I'm getting a wee bit jealous.

28:31.086 --> 28:33.046
- There's nothing to be jealous abo--

28:33.547 --> 28:34.882
Also, we're not a couple!

28:34.882 --> 28:37.634
- You're a detective.
Look at the evidence.

28:37.634 --> 28:39.136
We're a good match.

28:40.429 --> 28:43.599
You brought out something
in my bassoon playing.

28:43.599 --> 28:46.476
Something feral.
- Stop it.

28:46.476 --> 28:48.103
- Oh, Charles.

28:48.937 --> 28:51.940
If you wanted me to stop,
you'd just hang up.

28:55.235 --> 28:58.113
- I heard you talking
about Bunny this morning,

28:58.113 --> 29:01.325
make me think I should return
the money she gave me.

29:01.325 --> 29:03.035
I don't want any trouble.

29:03.035 --> 29:06.205
- This is a hell of a lot of money,
Ivan, doesn't look good.

29:07.706 --> 29:10.959
- For seven years, she was my regular.

29:10.959 --> 29:14.505
She always tipped me extra.
At first, just little.

29:15.631 --> 29:18.300
Then, even more generously.

29:18.300 --> 29:20.552
Maybe she saw me as grandson.

29:20.552 --> 29:23.180
Maybe she saw me as...

29:23.180 --> 29:24.806
something else.

29:24.806 --> 29:26.767
- [growls] This is...

29:26.767 --> 29:30.187
This is one layer of the onion
I did not need to peel back.

29:30.187 --> 29:31.855
[shudders]

29:31.855 --> 29:33.690
But, look...

29:33.690 --> 29:36.693
Is there anything about Bunny

29:37.861 --> 29:40.239
that you remember that could help?

29:40.239 --> 29:43.200
Anything about her final days
that were different?

29:43.200 --> 29:46.203
♪

29:55.879 --> 29:59.007
- It's so quiet in the building now.

29:59.007 --> 30:00.884
Aside from some yodeling.

30:00.884 --> 30:02.219
- Yodeling?

30:02.219 --> 30:05.138
- Yeah. Howard has a group. Don't ask.

30:05.138 --> 30:07.891
I miss the bassoon.
OPERATOR: You have one minute remaining.

30:08.934 --> 30:10.561
- I should go.
JAN: Wait.

30:10.561 --> 30:12.062
You know what I've been thinking about?

30:12.062 --> 30:14.273
It's warm and moist.

30:14.273 --> 30:16.525
There's a bit of sweetness in every bite.

30:17.734 --> 30:20.654
- Is it the food in prison?
JAN: Blech.

30:21.363 --> 30:24.366
I'm talking about
those blueberry bagels we had.

30:25.868 --> 30:27.870
Remember?
- Oh yeah.

30:29.037 --> 30:31.123
The morning after we first, uh...

30:31.123 --> 30:34.084
- You do remember.
- Yeah. [laughs]

30:34.084 --> 30:37.087
- You know, I bet those bagels
are still in your freezer.

30:38.088 --> 30:40.674
Just cold and lonely,

30:41.967 --> 30:44.761
waiting for someone
to come heat up their lives again

30:44.761 --> 30:46.471
like she did before.

30:47.639 --> 30:51.185
What I'd give to taste
one of those blueberry bad boys.

30:51.185 --> 30:52.436
- You know, Jan...
[soft click]

30:53.478 --> 30:57.316
neurotics make very good sex partners.

30:59.776 --> 31:01.028
Jan?

31:01.904 --> 31:03.155
Jan?

31:07.993 --> 31:10.287
IVAN: Now, the day before she died,
I took the day off,

31:10.287 --> 31:13.790
but I heard that Bunny
met with someone here.

31:13.790 --> 31:15.209
Someone who pissed her off.

31:15.209 --> 31:16.418
[plays tape]

31:16.418 --> 31:19.129
- Okay, you really need to upgrade to 4K.

31:19.129 --> 31:20.422
This is unwatchable.

31:21.131 --> 31:22.925
- I...
- Hold on.

31:24.176 --> 31:25.260
[beep]

31:26.136 --> 31:28.514
There, on the tape, was the murderer.

31:29.181 --> 31:30.349
Maybe.

31:30.349 --> 31:33.352
Looking... murderous.

31:34.269 --> 31:35.270
Possibly.

31:35.270 --> 31:37.022
And...

31:37.022 --> 31:38.273
grainy.

31:39.691 --> 31:42.778
Too grainy to make out any
physical characteristics at all.

31:42.778 --> 31:43.820
Oh, hold on.

31:45.113 --> 31:46.949
What was that?
What did they just pick up?

31:46.949 --> 31:49.451
- Nothing. That's where
we keep the matchbooks.

31:51.828 --> 31:53.330
- God, I'm good!

31:54.706 --> 31:55.958
[elevator dings]

31:57.876 --> 31:59.378
WILL:
You know, my dad

31:59.378 --> 32:01.964
isn't just good at figuring out
people's secrets.

32:04.258 --> 32:05.551
Hey! Dad!

32:05.551 --> 32:07.386
He can get obsessed with it.

32:09.388 --> 32:11.390
I could never figure out why.

32:13.267 --> 32:15.269
Maybe it makes you feel safe.

32:20.649 --> 32:21.942
Maybe it makes you feel needed.

32:22.609 --> 32:24.319
- Thank you for the bagels, Charles.

32:28.991 --> 32:30.784
WILL:
Or maybe it makes you feel powerful.

32:30.784 --> 32:33.954
[typing, sends text]

32:33.954 --> 32:36.957
♪

32:36.957 --> 32:39.251
But sometimes, it doesn't do any of that.

32:40.878 --> 32:43.005
Sometimes, it just makes you feel worse.

32:43.005 --> 32:45.299
- [sighs] So, what's up, baby?

32:46.925 --> 32:49.803
- So, uh, we got back the DNA test

32:49.803 --> 32:51.680
we took for Henry's school project.

32:51.680 --> 32:54.474
- Oh, is this about the predisposition
of prostate cancer?

32:54.474 --> 32:55.851
Dr. Kipper said it's no big deal.

32:55.851 --> 32:57.728
You just put your finger
up there twice a year,

32:57.728 --> 32:59.146
and then you phone someone you're fond of.

32:59.146 --> 33:01.481
- [laughs] No.
No, it-it's about the ancestry.

33:03.025 --> 33:05.194
Dad, are you sure you're 100% Irish?

33:05.944 --> 33:08.030
- [Irish accent]
Am I 100% Irish?

33:08.030 --> 33:10.949
I'll have you know I'm Putnam
through and through,

33:10.949 --> 33:13.994
and devil the man who say
a word agin me, you know.

33:13.994 --> 33:15.913
- Right. Um...

33:15.913 --> 33:18.957
You know, well, my DNA came back, and,

33:18.957 --> 33:20.959
you know, half was clearly Mom.

33:21.668 --> 33:24.463
But the other half was all Greek.

33:25.547 --> 33:27.424
That-that's not possible, is it?

33:27.424 --> 33:28.926
- Greek?

33:30.010 --> 33:32.012
No, that c-can't...

33:32.012 --> 33:34.973
♪

33:36.558 --> 33:38.977
[wind blowing]

33:38.977 --> 33:41.563
- Who's the Son of Sam tonight, Dad?

33:41.563 --> 33:43.482
- Oh, Teddy.

33:43.482 --> 33:46.235
It's always obvious
when he's hiding something.

33:46.235 --> 33:48.487
You're awfully quiet tonight, Teddy.

33:49.863 --> 33:51.281
What, do you have another secret?

33:51.740 --> 33:53.116
[quiet laugh]

34:00.541 --> 34:03.544
♪ Tell Me Something Good by Rufus ♪

34:05.462 --> 34:07.840
♪ Tell me, tell me, tell me ♪

34:07.840 --> 34:11.802
♪ Tell me that you love me, yeah ♪

34:14.388 --> 34:16.765
♪ Tell me something good ♪

34:18.475 --> 34:20.894
♪ Tell me, tell me, tell me ♪

34:20.894 --> 34:24.606
♪ Tell me that you like it, yeah ♪

34:27.401 --> 34:31.071
♪ "Got no time" is what ♪

34:31.071 --> 34:34.908
♪ You're known to say ♪

34:35.492 --> 34:37.119
♪ Got no time ♪

34:37.119 --> 34:39.997
♪ I bet you wish there was ♪

34:39.997 --> 34:43.959
♪ 48 hours to each day ♪

34:46.920 --> 34:49.381
♪ Tell me something good ♪

34:49.381 --> 34:53.051
♪ Oh baby, baby, baby, yeah... ♪
